# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: diacritical-mark
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:diacritical-mark/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] A **diacritic** (also **diacritical mark**, **diacritical point**, **diacritical sign**, or **accent**) is a glyph added to a letter or to a basic glyph.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The term derives from the Ancient Greek διακριτικός (*diakritikós*, "distinguishing"), from διακρίνω (*diakrínō*, "to distinguish").
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The word *diacritic* is a noun, though it is sometimes used in an attributive sense, whereas *diacritical* is only an adjective.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Some diacritics, such as the acute ⟨ó⟩, grave ⟨ò⟩, and circumflex ⟨ô⟩ (all shown above an 'o'), are often called *accents*.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Diacritics may appear above or below a letter or in some other position such as within the letter or between two letters.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The main use of diacritics in Latin script is to change the sound-values of the letters to which they are added.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Historically, English has used the diaeresis diacritic to indicate the correct pronunciation of ambiguous words, such as "coöperate", without which the <oo> letter sequence could be misinterpreted to be pronounced /ˈkuːpəreɪt/.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Most other words with diacritics in English are borrowings from languages such as French to better preserve the spelling, such as the diaeresis on *naïve* and *Noël*, the acute from *café*, the circumflex in the word *crêpe*, and the cedille in *façade*.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] All these diacritics, however, are frequently omitted in writing, and English is the only major modern European language that does not have diacritics in common usage.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In Latin-script alphabets in other languages diacritics may distinguish between homonyms, such as the French *là* ("there") versus *la* ("the"), which are both pronounced /la/.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In Gaelic type, a dot over a consonant indicates lenition of the consonant in question.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In other writing systems, diacritics may perform other functions.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Vowel pointing systems, namely the Arabic harakat and the Hebrew niqqud systems, indicate vowels that are not conveyed by the basic alphabet.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The Indic virama ( ् etc.) and the Arabic sukūn ( ـْـ ) mark the absence of vowels.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Other uses include the Early Cyrillic titlo stroke ( ◌҃ ) and the Hebrew gershayim ( ״ ), which, respectively, mark abbreviations or acronyms, and Greek diacritical marks, which showed that letters of the alphabet were being used as numerals.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In Vietnamese and the Hanyu Pinyin official romanization system for Mandarin in China, diacritics are used to mark the tones of the syllables in which the marked vowels occur.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In orthography and collation, a letter modified by a diacritic may be treated either as a new, distinct letter or as a letter–diacritic combination.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] This varies from language to language and may vary from case to case within a language.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In some cases, letters are used as "in-line diacritics", with the same function as ancillary glyphs, in that they modify the sound of the letter preceding them, as in the case of the "h" in the English pronunciation of "sh" and "th".
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Such letter combinations are sometimes even collated as a single distinct letter.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] For example, the spelling sch was traditionally often treated as a separate letter in German.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Words with that spelling were listed after all other words spelled with s in card catalogs in the Vienna public libraries, for example (before digitization).
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The tilde, dot, comma, titlo, apostrophe, bar, and colon are sometimes diacritical marks, but also have other uses.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Not all diacritics occur adjacent to the letter they modify.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In the Wali language of Ghana, for example, an apostrophe indicates a change of vowel quality, but occurs at the beginning of the word, as in the dialects *’Bulengee* and *’Dolimi*.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Because of vowel harmony, all vowels in a word are affected, so the scope of the diacritic is the entire word.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In abugida scripts, like those used to write Hindi and Thai, diacritics indicate vowels, and may occur above, below, before, after, or around the consonant letter they modify.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The tittle (dot) on the letter ⟨i⟩ or the letter ⟨j⟩, of the Latin alphabet originated as a diacritic to clearly distinguish ⟨i⟩ from the minims (downstrokes) of adjacent letters.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] It first appeared in the 11th century in the sequence *ii* (as in *ingeníí*), then spread to *i* adjacent to *m, n, u*, and finally to all lowercase *i*s.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The ⟨j⟩, originally a variant of *i*, inherited the tittle.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The shape of the diacritic developed from initially resembling today's acute accent to a long flourish by the 15th century.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] With the advent of Roman type it was reduced to the round dot we have today.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Several languages of eastern Europe use diacritics on both consonants and vowels, whereas in western Europe digraphs are more often used to change consonant sounds.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Most languages in Europe use diacritics on vowels, aside from English where there are typically none (with some exceptions).
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The diacritics **〮** and **〯** , known as Bangjeom (방점; 傍點), were used to mark pitch accents in Hangul for Middle Korean.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] They were written to the left of a syllable in vertical writing and above a syllable in horizontal writing.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In addition to the above vowel marks, transliteration of Syriac sometimes includes *ə*, *e̊* or superscript *e* (or often nothing at all) to represent an original Aramaic schwa that became lost later on at some point in the development of Syriac.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Some transliteration schemes find its inclusion necessary for showing spirantization or for historical reasons.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Some non-alphabetic scripts also employ symbols that function essentially as diacritics.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Different languages use different rules to put diacritic characters in alphabetical order.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] For example, French and Portuguese treat letters with diacritical marks the same as the underlying letter for purposes of ordering and dictionaries.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The Scandinavian languages and the Finnish language, by contrast, treat the characters with diacritics ⟨å⟩, ⟨ä⟩, and ⟨ö⟩ as distinct letters of the alphabet, and sort them after ⟨z⟩.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Usually ⟨ä⟩ (a-umlaut) and ⟨ö⟩ (o-umlaut) [used in Swedish and Finnish] are sorted as equivalent to ⟨æ⟩ (ash) and ⟨ø⟩ (o-slash) [used in Danish and Norwegian].
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Also, *aa*, when used as an alternative spelling to ⟨å⟩, is sorted as such.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Other letters modified by diacritics are treated as variants of the underlying letter, with the exception that ⟨ü⟩ is frequently sorted as ⟨y⟩.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Languages that treat accented letters as variants of the underlying letter usually alphabetize words with such symbols immediately after similar unmarked words.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] For instance, in German where two words differ only by an umlaut, the word without it is sorted first in German dictionaries (e.g.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] *schon* and then *schön*, or *fallen* and then *fällen*).
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] However, when names are concerned (e.g. in phone books or in author catalogues in libraries), umlauts are often treated as combinations of the vowel with a suffixed ⟨e⟩; Austrian phone books now treat characters with umlauts as separate letters (immediately following the underlying vowel).
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In Spanish, the grapheme ⟨ñ⟩ is considered a distinct letter, different from ⟨n⟩ and collated between ⟨n⟩ and ⟨o⟩, as it denotes a different sound from that of a plain ⟨n⟩.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] But the accented vowels ⟨á⟩, ⟨é⟩, ⟨í⟩, ⟨ó⟩, ⟨ú⟩ are not separated from the unaccented vowels ⟨a⟩, ⟨e⟩, ⟨i⟩, ⟨o⟩, ⟨u⟩, as the acute accent in Spanish only modifies stress within the word or denotes a distinction between homonyms, and does not modify the sound of a letter.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] For a comprehensive list of the collating orders in various languages, see Collating sequence.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Modern computer technology was developed mostly in countries that speak Western European languages (particularly English), and many early binary encodings were developed with a bias favoring English—a language written without diacritical marks.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] With computer memory and computer storage at premium, early character sets were limited to the Latin alphabet, the ten digits and a few punctuation marks and conventional symbols.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII), first published in 1963, encoded just 95 printable characters.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] It included just four free-standing diacritics—acute, grave, circumflex and tilde—which were to be used by backspacing and overprinting the base letter.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The ISO/IEC 646 standard (1967) defined national variations that replace some American graphemes with precomposed characters (such as ⟨é⟩, ⟨è⟩ and ⟨ë⟩), according to language—but remained limited to 95 printable characters.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Unicode was conceived to solve this problem by assigning every known character its own code; if this code is known, most modern computer systems provide a method to input it.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] For historical reasons, almost all the letter-with-accent combinations used in European languages were given unique code points and these are called precomposed characters.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] For other languages, it is usually necessary to use a combining character diacritic together with the desired base letter.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Unfortunately, even as of 2024, many applications and web browsers remain unable to operate the combining diacritic concept properly.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Depending on the keyboard layout and keyboard mapping, it is more or less easy to enter letters with diacritics on computers and typewriters.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] Keyboards used in countries where letters with diacritics are the norm, have keys engraved with the relevant symbols.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] In other cases, such as when the US international or UK extended mappings are used, the accented letter is created by first pressing the key with the diacritic mark, followed by the letter to place it on.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] This method is known as the dead key technique, as it produces no output of its own but modifies the output of the key pressed after it.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p01] The following languages have letters with diacritics that are orthographically distinct from those without diacritics.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] English is one of the few European languages that does not have many words that contain diacritical marks.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] Instead, digraphs are the main way the Modern English alphabet adapts the Latin to its phonemes.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] Exceptions are unassimilated foreign loanwords, including borrowings from French (and, increasingly, Spanish, like *jalapeño* and *piñata*); however, the diacritic is also sometimes omitted from such words.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] Loanwords that frequently appear with the diacritic in English include *café*, *résumé* or *resumé* (a usage that helps distinguish it from the verb *resume*), *soufflé*, and *naïveté* (see *English terms with diacritical marks*).
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] English speakers and writers once used the diaeresis more often than now in words such as *coöperation* (from Fr.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] *zoologia*), and *seeër* (now more commonly *see-er*or simply*seer*) as a way of indicating that adjacent vowels belonged to separate syllables, but this practice has become far less common.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] *The New Yorker* magazine is a major publication that continues to use the diaeresis in place of a hyphen for clarity and economy of space.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] A few English words, often when used out of context, especially in isolation, can only be distinguished from other words of the same spelling by using a diacritic or modified letter.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] The acute and grave accents are occasionally used in poetry and lyrics: the acute to indicate stress overtly where it might be ambiguous (*rébel* vs.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] *rebél*) or nonstandard for metrical reasons (*caléndar*), the grave to indicate that an ordinarily silent or elided syllable is pronounced (*warnèd,* *parlìament*).
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] In certain personal names such as *Renée* and *Zoë*, often two spellings exist, and the person's own preference will be known only to those close to them.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] They also appear in some worldwide company names and/or trademarks, such as *Nestlé* and *Citroën*.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] The following languages have letter-diacritic combinations that are not considered independent letters.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] Several languages that are not written with the Roman alphabet are transliterated, or romanized, using diacritics.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] Possibly the greatest number of combining diacritics *required* to compose a valid character in any Unicode language is 8, for the "well-known grapheme cluster in Tibetan and Ranjana scripts" or *HAKṢHMALAWARAYAṀ*.
[src:diacritical-mark/diacritic-p02] Some users have explored the limits of rendering in web browsers and other software by "decorating" words with excessive nonsensical diacritics per character to produce so-called Zalgo text.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:diacritical-mark/noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
